  [33m> Write[0m(file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/duh/benchmarks/double-agent-tdd/worktrees/duh-deepseek-v4-pro/docs/adrs/ADR-076-double-agent-tdd.md', content='# ADR-076: Double-Agent TDD Flow\n\n**Status:** Accepted\n**Date:** 2026-07-16\n\n## Context\n\nTest-Driven Development (TDD) is a well-established discipline: write a failing\ntest first (RED), write the minimum code to make it pass (GREEN), then refactor\nwhile keeping tests green (REFACTOR). When practiced with pair programming, it\nbecomes even more rigorous — the Driver writes the code while the Navigator\nreviews each step.\n\nD.U.H. already has multi-agent support (ADR-012) with AgentTool and SwarmTool\nfor spawning child engines. This ADR proposes a structured **double-agent TDD\nflow** where two cooperating agents — a **Driver** and a **Navigator** —\nexecute the red-green-refactor cycle under a strict six-phase protocol.\n\n### Why not just tell a single agent to "do TDD"?\n\nA single agent can be told to write tests and code, but it has no structural\nenforcement of the TDD discipline. It can skip RED, write\rtest-after code, or\nskip refactoring. The double-agent flow enforces:\n\n- The test MUST fail before any implementation code is written.\n- The Navigator reviews the test before RED and suggests refactors after GREEN.\n- The refactor MUST be applied and validated.\n\nThe Navigator acts as a constraint checker — it can force the Driver to tighten\na spec if the test passes prematurely (indicating the test wasn\'t actually\ntesting new behavior).\n\n## Decision\n\n### 1. Two cooperating agents: Driver and Navigator\n\n- **Driver** — writes the failing test (RED), writes the minimum code (GREEN),\n  applies refactors (REFACTOR). The Driver is a `coder`-type agent with full\n  tool access (Read, Write, Edit, Bash for running tests).\n- **Navigator** — drafts the test spec before RED, reviews the RED result,\n  proposes refactors after GREEN, validates the final refactor. The Navigator\n  is a `reviewer`-type agent with read-only access plus the ability to\n  instruct the Driver.\n\n### 2. Six-phase protocol, strict order\n\nThe flow proceeds through exactly six phases. Each phase must complete before\nthe next begins:\n\n| # | Phase | Actor | Action | Exit condition |\n|---|-------|-------|--------|----------------|\n| 1 | **SPEC** | Navigator | Drafts the test spec: what to test, expected behavior, edge cases. Output is a natural-language spec. | Spec approved by user or auto-proceed. |\n| 2 | **RED** | Driver | Writes the failing test based on the spec. Tests are executed. | Test MUST fail. If it passes, return to phase 1 (Navigator tightens spec). |\n| 3 | **GREEN** | Driver | Writes the minimum code to make the test pass. Tests executed. | Test MUST pass. |\n| 4 | **REFACTOR_PROPOSE** | Navigator | Reviews the GREEN code and proposes a refactor. Output is a list of specific changes. | Refactor proposal produced. |\n| 5 | **REFACTOR_APPLY** | Driver | Applies the Navigator\'s refactor suggestions. Tests executed. | Tests MUST still pass after refactor. |\n| 6 | **VALIDATE** | Navigator | Validates tests still pass and the refactor landed cleanly. Reports final status. | Validation complete (pass or fail). |\n\n### 3. Subcommand: `duh tdd`\n\nThe flow is exposed as a new subcommand:\n\n```\nduh tdd --prompt "Add a divide(a, b) function that raises on zero division"\n```\n\nIt accepts the same `--model`, `--provider`, `--max-turns`, and other flags\nthe rest of D.U.H. supports. The subcommand runs the six-phase protocol to\ncompletion and exits with status 0 (all phases passed) or non-zero (phase\nfailed).\n\n### 4. Reuses existing abstractions\n\n- **Engine** — each phase runs the Driver or Navigator agent through an Engine\n  instance (same pattern as AgentTool/SwarmTool).\n- **AgentDef / run_agent** — the Driver is `agent_type="coder"`, the Navigator\n  is `agent_type="reviewer"`. No new agent types needed.\n- **PlanMode** — the phase sequencing is similar to PlanMode (two-phase\n  orchestration), but specialized for TDD. We borrow the pattern, not the code.\n- **StubProvider** — tests use the same stub provider for deterministic\n  offline testing.\n\n### 5. Contract between Driver and Navigator\n\nThe information flow between agents is structured:\n\n```\nNavigator → Driver:  test spec (phase 1), refactor suggestion (phase 4)\nDriver → Navigator:  test code + result (phase 2), impl code + result (phase 3),\n                     refactored code + result (phase 5)\n```\n\nEach handoff uses a prompt format that the receiving agent can parse:\n\n```\n[SPEC]\n<Navigator\'s test spec>\n\n[INSTRUCTION]\nWrite a failing test that covers the spec above. Use the project\'s test framework.\n```\n\nThis structured format keeps the agents\' prompts parseable and avoids\nambiguity about what phase they\'re13 in.\n\n### 6. Phase failure handling\n\n- **Phase 2 RED failure** (test passes): return to phase 1. The Navigator gets\n  the passing test output and revises the spec to be tighter (e.g., "the test\n  passes because the function already exists — revise to test the *new*\n  behavior"). Maximum 3 spec revision cycles before reporting failure.\n- **Phase 3 GREEN failure** (test still fails): the Driver retries once. If\n  still failing, report the failure and exit.\n- **Phase 6 VALIDATE failure**: report which tests failed and exit with error.\n\n### 7. API\n\nA public Python API is also available:\n\n```python\nfrom duh.tools.double_agent_tdd import run_tdd_flow, TddResult\n\nresult: TddResult = await run_tdd_flow(\n    task="Add a divide(a, b) function",\n    deps=deps,\n    tools=tools,\n    model="claude-sonnet-4-6",\n)\n# result.phases  — list of (phase_name, success, output) tuples\n# result.success — True if all six phases passed\n```\n\n## Alternatives Considered\n\n### A. Single agent with prompt injection\n\nTell a single agent "do TDD." Simple, but no structural enforcement. The agent\ncan skip RED, write code before tests, etc. Rejected because the whole point\nis the enforced discipline.\n\n### B. New agent types: "driver" and "navigator"\n\nCreate two new `AGENT_OVERLAYS` entries. Overkill — the existing `coder` and\n`reviewer` types already capture the right behaviors. The TDD-specific prompts\nare injected as phase-specific instruction prefixes.\n\n### C. SwarmTool-based parallel execution\n\nUse SwarmTool to run Driver/Navigator in parallel. Doesn\'t work because the\nphases are strictly sequential — Navigator\'s spec must complete before Driver\nwrites tests, etc.\n\n### D. Hook-based enforcement\n\nUse hooks to enforce TDD discipline on a single agent. Possible but fragile —\nhooks can block/rewrite tool calls but can\'t force the agent to follow a\nsix-phase sequence. Hooks are14 for safety, not workflow orchestration.\n\n## Consequences\n\n- New `duh tdd` subcommand with six-phase execution.\n- Driver uses `coder` agent type, Navigator uses `reviewer` agent type.\n- Each phase is a child Engine run with phase-specific prompts.\n- Tests exercise the full flow against StubProvider.\n- No new agent overlays, no new kernel abstractions — reuses Engine + run_agent.')


